<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-325-072  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 325 072.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  April 2 1990 n584 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Japan opens its satellite market to U.S., others.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lammers, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Japanese government will cancel a government communicationssatellite program that excludes US participation and will open itscommercial satellite market to domestic and foreign firms in anattempt to resolve disputes arising from the US-Japan 301satellite talks.andP;  A delegation from the Japanese governmentpresented what a source called the country's final compromiseproposal; the US Trade Representative office declined to comment,but its reaction to the proposal is expected to affect itsrecommendation to the Bush administration on possible sanctions.andO;The sanctions are being considered to counter Japan's closedsupercomputer, satellite and wood products markets and may include100 percent tariffs.andP;  The Japanese government reportedly hasoffered to cancel the CS4 communications satellite program infavor of an experimental data relay tracking satellite to belaunched in 1995 or 1996.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     JapanExportCommunications SatellitesMarket EntryCompetitionPolitical IssuesInternational TradeSatellite CommunicationsForeign Competition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>